[[File:Tom Thomson headstone.jpg|thumb|Tom Thomson's headstone in [[Meaford, Ontario]]. Thomson's part of the stone bears the inscription: ''Tom Thomson Landscape painter Drowned in Canoe Lake July 8 1917 aged 39 years 11 months 3 days''.]]

The '''death of Tom Thomson''', the Canadian painter, occurred on 8 July 1917, on [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]] in [[Algonquin Provincial Park]] in [[Nipissing District, Ontario|Nipissing District]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. After Thomson drowned in the water, his upturned canoe was discovered later that afternoon and his body eight days later. Many theories regarding Thomson's death—including that he was murdered or committed suicide—have become popular in the years since his death, though these ideas lack any substantiation.

Thomson stands tall as a figure in [[Canadian art]]. His later work has had a profound influence on both the artists contemporary to him as well as those coming much later. Paintings such as ''[[The Jack Pine]]'' and ''[[The West Wind (painting)|The West Wind]]'' have taken a prominent place in the [[culture of Canada]] and are some of the country's most iconic pieces of art. In addition to his prominence as an artist, he has developed a reputation as an ideal Canadian [[Outdoor enthusiast|outdoorsman]], proficient in [[canoe]]ing and fishing, though his talents in the former have come to be doubted.

==Background==

===The outdoorsman===

[[File:Tom Thomson, standing on a rock fishing in moving water.jpg|thumb|Thomson fishing at Tea Lake Dam in [[Algonquin Park]], {{circa|lk=no|1915/16}}]]

Though he is most known for his painting, [[Tom Thomson]] is often mythologized as a veritable [[Outdoor enthusiast|outdoorsman]].{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=236}} He was taken out of school at an early age, possibly due to a lung condition.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=41}}{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}}{{sfnb|MacDonald|1917|p=47}} This afforded him time to explore wooded areas and develop a deep appreciation for nature.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=4}} He spent much of his time on walks with his grandmother's first cousin, Dr. William Brodie, a well known [[Entomology|entomologist]], [[Ornithology|ornithologist]] and [[Botany|botanist]].{{sfnb|Murray|1999|pp=6–7}}{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|p=93}} He similarly developed a love for both fishing and hunting,{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|pp=28–29}}{{sfnb|Murray|2015|loc="Prologue"}} though he eventually gave up hunting after shooting a deer "as the look in its eyes was too human."{{sfnb|Murray|2015|loc="Prologue"}}{{sfnb|Henry|1931}}

Dr. [[James MacCallum]] contributed stories to Thomson's image as an outdoorsman, including one story that Thomson encountered a large wolf who, after sniffing him briefly, left him alone.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=236}} He further wrote, {{quote|[Thomson] was wont to paddle out into the centre of the lake on which he happened to be camping and spend the whole night there in order to get away from the flies and mosquitos {{sic}}. Motionless he studied the night skies and the changing outline of the shores while beaver and otter played around his canoe.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=236}}{{sfnb|MacCallum|1918|p=382}}}}

Thomson has often been remembered as an expert [[wiktionary:canoeist|canoeist]]. David Silcox has argued that this image is likely romanticized.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=237}} [[A. Y. Jackson]] wrote that Thomson "paddled like an [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indian]]," holding his abilities in high esteem.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=237}} Despite this, Park ranger Mark Robinson said that Thomson admitted to him in 1913 that he did not know much about canoeing.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=237}} In addition, there are multiple stories of him capsizing.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=15}}{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=215, 237}}{{sfnb|Wadland|2002|pp=94–95}} In 1912, after hearing that Thomson had capsized and lost most of his supplies on a canoeing trip up the Mississagi River, friend John McRuer replied saying, "You might have been drowned you devil; and that was not the first time you were bumped, eh!"{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=237}}

Despite these romantic images, an area that Thomson was no doubt proficient in was fishing. The deep love of fishing he developed while young remained for his entire life, so much so that his reputation through Algonquin Park was equally divided between art and [[angling]].{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|pp=28, 28n39}} While most who visited the Park were led by hired guides, Thomson moved through on his own. Indeed, many of his fishing locations appear in his work.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=29}} Upon visiting Canoe Lake for the first time in 1914, A. Y. Jackson wrote to [[J. E. H. MacDonald]], "It appears that Tom Thomson is some fisherman, quite noted round here."{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=28}}{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=123}}{{sfnb|Jackson|1914}}

[[File:Thomson, Path Behind Mowat Lodge.jpg|thumb|left|''Path Behind Mowat Lodge'', Spring 1917. [[Art Gallery of Ontario]], [[Toronto]]]]

===1917 sketching season===
{{Further information|Tom Thomson#Artistic peak (1916-17)|Artistic development of Tom Thomson#Creative peak (1916–17)}}
{{See also|Artistic development of Tom Thomson#Approaching abstraction}}

From 1914 onward, Thomson regularly traveled to [[Algonquin Provincial Park|Algonquin Park]] in the spring, either camping on [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]] or staying at the Mowat Lodge hotel. He spent his time there sketching and working as a fishing guide, returning to [[Toronto]] in the fall, producing larger canvas works from his original sketches.{{sfnb|Murray|2015|loc="From the Studio Building to Algonquin Park and Home Again"}} In 1917 Thomson returned to Canoe Lake at the beginning of April, arriving early enough to paint the remaining snow and the ice breaking up on the surrounding lakes.{{sfnb|Murray|2015|loc="From the Studio Building to Algonquin Park and Home Again"}}{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=141}} The paintings became his own visual diary of the day,{{sfnb|Murray|2015|loc="From the Studio Building to Algonquin Park and Home Again"}}{{sfnb|Robinson|1930|p=3}} morphing into a [[Serial imagery|series]] that he described as, "a record of the weather for 62 days, rain or shine, or snow, dark or bright."{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=116}} He wrote home to his father saying that, though he had not sold many sketches that year, that he thought he could "get along for another year at least while I stick to painting as long as I can."{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|pp=303–04}} In his final letter to MacCallum—sent only one day before his disappearance—he complained of flies and [[mosquito]]es. He had not done much sketching since they emerged but was hopeful the warmer weather would soon kill them off. He promised to send along some of his winter sketches and was looking forward to sketching on several trips planned for the next two months.{{sfnb|Thomson|1917b}}{{efn|group=note|Mowat P. O., July 7, 1917<br>Dear Sir:<br>I am still around Frasers and have not done any sketching since the flies started. The weather has been wet and cold all spring and the flies and mosquitos much worse than I have seen them any year and the [[Insect repellent|fly dope]] doesnt {{sic}} have any effect on them. This however is the second warm day we have had this year and another day or so like this will finish them. Will send my winter sketches down in a day or two and have every intention of making some more but it has been almost impossible lately. Have done a great deal of paddling this spring and the fishing has been fine. Have done some guiding for fishing parties and will have some other trips this month and next with probably sketching in between. [...]<br>Hoping you are well, I am<br>Yours truly / Tom Thomson{{sfnb|Thomson|1917b}}{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|p=306}}}}

The works he completed over this spring display the masterful control of colour he had come to develop—especially apparent in a painting like ''The Rapids''{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=17}}—and are painted with a particular "crispness and freshness."{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=141}} His sketches in particular show how he matured into "a subtlety of expression, using a brisk but delicate handling."{{sfnb|Murray|2015|loc="From the Studio Building to Algonquin Park and Home Again"}} The bold and expressive brushstrokes that he is now famous for are evident in paintings like ''Path Behind Mowat Lodge'' and ''Tea Lake Dam''.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|pp=17–18}} Also on display in the former are small areas of bare wood panel, visible through the paint. This device further adds to the lighting of the scene.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|pp=74–75}} The aggressive style of painting Thomson utilized was seen consistently in the [[Expressionism|Expressionist]] movement that followed his death.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=73}} His final works have been described by [[art history|art historians]] David Silcox and [[Harold Town]] as moving in the direction of [[abstract art|abstraction]].{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|pp=17–18, 44, 52, 57, 62, 68, 73}}{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=148}}{{efn|group=note|For more regarding Thomson's later abstract tendencies, refer to: {{bulleted list|{{harvp|Silcox|2015|p=44}}|{{harvp|Silcox|Town|2017|pp=148–49}}|{{section link|Artistic development of Tom Thomson#Approaching abstraction}}
}}}} This is especially evident in what is perhaps his final work, ''After the Storm'', which, "When viewed up close, Thomson’s thick, broad application of paint in this landscape melts into pure abstraction."{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=52}} The landscapes of his final works in late spring and early summer often contain these types of bold, generalized forms.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=142}}

Besides the deep love he had come to develop for Algonquin Park, Thomson was beginning to show an eagerness to depict areas beyond the park and explore other northern subjects.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=18}} In a May 1917 letter to his brother-in-law, he wrote:

{{quote|I may possibly go out on the [[Canadian Northern Railway|Canadian Northern [Railway]]] this summer to paint the [[Canadian Rockies|Rockys]] {{sic}} but have not made all the arrangements yet. If I go it will be in July & August.{{sfnb|Thomson|1917a}}{{sfnb|Murray|2002a|pp=304–05}}}}

A. Y. Jackson suggested Thomson would have traveled even further north, just as the other members of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]] eventually did.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=122}}

