==Death==
On the morning of 8 July 1917, Thomson was seen walking to Joe Lake Dam with Shannon Fraser, the owner of the Mowat Lodge.{{sfnb|Murray|2002b|p=317}} He often spent his night there when the park proved too cold for camping.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=18}} Mark Robinson, a [[park ranger]], noted in his diary that Thomson "left Fraser's Dock after 12:30 pm to go to Tea Lake Dam or West Lake."{{sfnb|Murray|2002b|p=317}} Thomson disappeared during this canoeing trip on Canoe Lake.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=49}}{{efn|group=note|On 10 July, Fraser sent a telegram to MacCallum, writing:

{{quote|DR MCCALLUM {{sic}}

BLULER (Bloor) ST TORONTO ONT

TOMES {{sic}} CANOE FOUND UPSIDE DOWN NO TRACE OF TOM SUNCE {{sic}} SUNDAY NOON

J S FRASER{{sfnb|Fraser|1917a}}}}}}{{efn|group=note|A popular—if unverifiable—story recounts that he was attempting to catch a particularly large bass on Joe Lake the day he disappeared.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|loc=p. 28n39}}}} His upturned canoe was spotted later in the afternoon, while his body was discovered in the lake eight days later on 16 July.{{sfnb|Murray|2002b|p=317}}{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=49}}{{efn|group=note|The telegram from J.S. Fraser to Tom's brother John read simply: {{quote|Canoe Lake Ont July 16–17

J Thomson
Owen Sound.

:Found tom {{sic}} this morning.

J S Fraser{{sfnb|Fraser|1917b}}}}}} His watch had stopped at 12:14{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=142}}{{sfnb|Thomson|1934}} and he had a four inch bruise on his right temple.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=23}}

The body was examined by Dr. Goldwin Howland who concluded that the official cause of death was drowning.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=49}}{{sfnb|Howland|1917}}{{efn|group=note|Howland later recounted the following: {{quote|I saw body of man floating in Canoe Lake Monday, July 16th, at about 10 A. M. and notified Mr. George Rowe a resident who removed body to shore. On 17th Tuesday, I examined [the body] and found it to be that of a man aged about 40 years in advanced stage of decomposition, face abdomen and limbs swollen, blisters on limbs, was a bruise on right temple size of 4" long, no other sign of external marks visible on body, air issuing from mouth, some bleeding from right ear, cause of death drowning.{{sfnb|Howland|1917}}}}}} The coroner, Dr. Arthur E. Ranney, supported Howland's conclusion that the drowning was accidental, further writing that "the evidence from the other six witnesses points that the cause of death was drowning."{{sfnb|Ranney|1931}} Regarding the four inch bruise on Thomson's temple, he wrote that, "no doubt, [it] was caused by stricking {{sic}} some [obstacle], like a stone, when the body was drowned."{{sfnb|Ranney|1931}}

The day after the body was discovered, it was interred in Mowat Cemetery near Canoe Lake.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=49}}{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=142}}{{sfnb|Robinson|1917}}{{efn|group=note|Mowat Cemetery was located at {{coord|45|33|47|N|78|43|42|W}}.}} Under the direction of Thomson's older brother George, the body was exhumed two days later and was shipped to [[Owen Sound]]. It was re-interred in the family plot beside the Leith Presbyterian Church on 21 July in what is now the Municipality of [[Meaford, Ontario|Meaford]].<ref>{{plainlist|
* {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=142}}
* {{harvp|Murray|2002b|p=317}}
* {{harvp|Silcox|Town|2017|p=49–50}}
}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.meaford.ca/tourism/plan-trip-meaford/what-to-do/heritage-arts-culture/175-historic-leith-church.html|title=Historic Leith Church|last=|first=|date=|website=www.meaford.ca|language=en-gb|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref>

[[Image:Tom Thomson Memorial Cairn.jpg|thumb|The Tom Thomson Memorial Cairn, [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]], [[Algonquin Park]]]]
With financial assistance provided by MacCallum, on 27 September 1917 J. E. H. MacDonald, [[John William Beatty]], Shannon Fraser, George Rowe and local residents erected a memorial [[cairn]] at Hayhurst Point on Canoe Lake, where Thomson died.<ref>{{plainlist|
* {{harvp|Hill|2002|p=142}}
* {{harvp|Murray|2002b|p=317}}
* {{harvp|Silcox|2006|p=213}}
* {{harvp|Silcox|Town|2017|p=240}}
}}</ref>{{efn|group=note|MacDonald wrote to Thomson's father, {{quote|I have just returned from Canoe Lake where I spent the weekend helping Mr. [J. W.] Beatty to put on the plate and give the cairn a few finishing touches. The cairn is a fine piece of work, and with the brass plate in position it looks quite imposing. It stands on a prominent point in Canoe Lake right at the head of the lake facing north and can be seen from all directions. It is situated near an old favorite camping spot of Tom's. [...] The result goes a long way to beautifying the tragedy of Tom's death.{{sfnb|MacDonald|1917}}}}}} Because of Thomson's deep love for the area, the Group "had not the heart to go back to Algonquin Park, so they moved to [[Algoma District|Algoma]] and [[Lake Superior]], and then to the [[Arctic]], [[Yukon]], [[Labrador]], and other parts of the country."{{sfnb|Roza|1997|p=31}}{{sfnb|Jackson|1919|p=5}}

==Legacy==
{{Quote box|width=30em|align=left|quote="Your Canadian art apparently, for now at least, went down in [[Canoe Lake (Nipissing District)|Canoe Lake]]. Tom Thomson still stands as ''the'' Canadian painter, harsh, brilliant, brittle, uncouth, not only most Canadian but most creative. How the few things of his stick in one's mind."|source=—[[David Milne (artist)|David Milne]] in a letter to [[National Gallery of Canada#Directors|H. O. McCurry]], 1930{{sfnb|Milne|1930}}{{sfnb|Dejardin|2018|pp=17, 194}}}}
Since his death, Thomson's work has grown in value and popularity. Scholar Sherrill Grace has written that Thomson is a "haunting presence" for Canadian artists and that he "embodies the Canadian artistic identity."{{sfnb|Grace|2004|p=96}} Group of Seven member [[Arthur Lismer]] similarly wrote that "Tom Thomson is the manifestation of the Canadian character."{{sfnb|Lismer|1934|pp=163–64}}

In 2002, the National Gallery of Canada staged a major exhibition of his work, giving Thomson the same level of prominence afforded [[Picasso]], [[Pierre-Auguste Renoir|Renoir]], and the Group of Seven in previous years.{{sfnb|Reid|2002a}} As of 2009, the highest price achieved by a Thomson sketch was ''Early Spring, Canoe Lake'' (1917) which sold in 2009 for $2,749,500 ({{Inflation|CA|2749500|2009|fmt=eq|r=-3|cursign=[[Canadian Dollar|CAD$]]}}). Few major canvases remain in private collections, making the record unlikely to be broken.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=66}} One example of the demand Thomson's work has achieved is the previously lost ''Sketch for Lake in Algonquin Park'' (1912/13). The painting was discovered in an [[Edmonton]] basement in 2018 and went on to sell for nearly half a million dollars at a Toronto auction.{{sfnb|Vikander|2018}}{{sfnb|The Canadian Press|2018}} The increased value of Thomson's work has led to the discovery of numerous [[art forgery|forgeries]] of his work on the market.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=182}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=74}}{{sfnb|Dellandrea|2017}}

[[File:TomThomsonGallery.JPG|thumb|The Tom Thomson Art Gallery in [[Owen Sound]] has a large collection of Thomson artworks, especially from his earlier career.]]

In the summer of 2004 another historical marker honouring Thomson was moved from its previous location nearer the centre of Leith to the graveyard in which Thomson is now buried. The grave site has become popular spot for visitors to the area with many fans of Thomson's work leaving pennies or small art supplies behind as tribute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heritagemeaford.com/heritage-church.php?mid=1|title=Leith United Church {{!}} Heritage Meaford|website=www.heritagemeaford.com|access-date=16 January 2018}}</ref> 

In 1967, the Tom Thomson Art Gallery opened in Owen Sound.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Thomson Art Gallery|url=https://www.tomthomson.org/|publisher=City of Owen Sound}}</ref> In 1968 Thomson's shack from behind the [[Studio Building (Toronto)|Studio Building]] was moved to the [[McMichael Canadian Art Collection]] in [[Kleinburg]].{{sfnb|Dexter|1968}} Numerous examples of his work are also on display at the National Gallery of Canada in Ottawa, the Art Gallery of Ontario, and the McMichael Canadian Art Collection in Kleinburg, Ontario. Thomson's influence can be seen in the work of later Canadian artists, including [[Emily Carr]], Goodridge Roberts, Harold Town, and [[Joyce Wieland]].{{sfnb|Stanners|2017}}

===An "untainted" artist===
In the years since his death, Thomson has often been described as being independent of previous artistic traditions.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=29–30, 212}}{{sfnb|Roza|1997|pp=29–30}}{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=85}} Many have pointed to the fact that he never visited Europe or museums in the [[United States]] as evidence that he managed to avoid the developments of [[Modern art|Modernist]] experiment.{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=85}} Thomson's lack of formal art education similarly caused the other members of the group to later see him as a natural, untainted artist, and this view has entered the myth and public perception surrounding him.{{sfnb|Roza|1997|pp=29–30}}{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=29–30}}

David Silcox and Andrew Hunter have argued that these perceptions were primarily propagated by his friends, those who formed the Group of Seven in the years following his death and others in the Canadian art scene,{{efn|group=note|Hunter has pointed to F. B. Housser, Newton McTavish, Albert H. Robson, [[Barker Fairley]], [[Harold Mortimer-Lamb]] and Dr. [[James MacCallum]] as being major influences in propagating the Thomson legends.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=35}}}} nearly all of whom relied on the same basic details in their treatments of Thomson's life and career.{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=35}} Lismer, for example, wrote, "[Thomson] had no connection with styles or schools... He had nothing to do with Europe and in his art there is not a trace of inherited style or influence from abroad... If one  knew Thomson, one also realized that he knew nothing of such as things as <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Art Nouveau]] or [[Impressionism]]<nowiki>]</nowiki>."{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=85}} Jackson similarly wrote that Thomson's "rugged individuality was never dominated by any outside influence,"{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=85}} and that Thomson was the "Instigator of the movement to the North Country."{{sfnb|Jackson|1935}} [[Lawren Harris]] echoed these views, saying "There was nothing that interfered with Tom's direct, primal vision of nature. He was completely innocent of any of the machinery of civilization and was happiest when away from it in the north."{{sfnb|McInnes|1944}} Barker Fairley wrote that, "Neither theory nor any acquired opinion can have had any permanent place in Thomson's mind. He was naïve throughout."{{sfnb|Fairley|1920|p=246}} Harold Mortimer-Lamb wrote, "With his equipment he went to Nature and communed with her in all her moods."{{sfnb|Mortimer-Lamb|1919|p=124}} Blodwen Davies wrote, "Through the story of painting in Canada there stalks a tall, lean trailsman, with his sketch box and paddle, an artist and dreamer who made the wilderness his cloister and there worshipped Nature in her secret moods."{{sfnb|Hunter|2002|p=36}}{{sfnb|Davies|1930}} F. B. Housser wrote, "Never before had such knowledge and the feeling for such things been given to expression in paint. Thomson's canvases are unique in the annals of all art especially when it is remembered that he was untrained as a painter. His master was nature."{{sfnb|Housser|1926}} In general, members of the Group claimed that their art did not originate in established artistic traditions but was instead dictated by the landscape itself.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=29–30, 212}}{{efn|group=note|For example, see: {{bulleted list|{{harvp|Harris|1929|p=185}}|{{harvp|Jackson|1958|p=22}}}}}} A. Y. Jackson described Thomson as "the guide, the interpreter" who introduced his friends to "a new world, the north country."{{sfnb|Roza|1997|loc=p. 30n29}}{{sfnb|Reid|1971|p=90}} Dennis Reid argued similarly, writing that Thomson's death was seen "almost as a sacrifice to the idea of an indigenous Canadian art... Thomson was... to become Canada's first Old Master, and as an idea he has acted as a constant inspiration to all who believed that the secret of Canada's self-knowledge is somehow contained in the land."{{sfnb|Roza|1997|loc=p. 30n29}}{{sfnb|Reid|1971|p=90}} [[Historical revisionism|Revisionist art historians]] have criticized the view that Thomson and the Group of Seven were originators of a new [[Canadian nationalism|Canadian nationalist]] style of art.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=58}}{{efn|group=note|For example, see: {{bulleted list|{{harvp|Dawn|2007}}|{{harvp|Jessup|2007}}|{{harvp|McKay|2011|loc=Ch. 8–9}}
}}}}

Despite the popular notion that Thomson had no formal art instruction, it is possible that he briefly studied under [[Art of the United Kingdom|British artist]] [[William Cruikshank (painter)|William Cruikshank]] around 1905.<ref>{{plainlist|
* {{harvp|Murray|1986|p=6}}
* {{harvp|Reid|2002b|p=70}}
* {{harvp|Silcox|Town|2017|p=43}}
* {{harvp|Stacey|2002|p=52}}
}}</ref> Only two sources corroborate this however. The first is a single undated note from Cruikshank to professor [[James Mavor]], arranging to bring a "Tomson" {{sic}} to meet him.{{sfnb|Cruikshank}}{{sfnb|Reid|2002b|loc=p. 70n21}} Further complicating the matter is that the original class list no longer survives.{{sfnb|Reid|2002b|loc=p. 70n21}} The second is a letter from H. B. Jackson to Blodwen Davies, writing, "Tom studied from life & the antique in art school. If I remember right Cruikshank was the instructor."{{sfnb|Jackson|1931}}{{sfnb|Hill|2002|loc=p. 113n18}} Besides in-person instruction, it is also possible that he read [[John Ruskin]]'s 1857 handbook, ''[[The Elements of Drawing]]'', while learning to draw.{{sfnb|Murray|1999|p=2}} Outside of these possibilities, it seems that he had no other art instruction.{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=9}} Thomson's work in commercial art however did seem to have an influence on his painting, leading him to familiarity with the Art Nouveau as well as Arts and Crafts movements.{{sfnb|Hill|2002|p=113}}{{sfnb|Reid|2002b|pp=65–83}} Similarly, working with his fellow artists caused him to become aware of the techniques of [[Impressionism]] and [[Post-Impressionism]].{{sfnb|Roza|1997|p=30n29}}{{sfnb|Silcox|Town|2017|p=88}} Regarding Art Nouveau tendencies, Jackson wrote that, "We (the Group of Seven and Tom Thomson) treated our subjects with the freedom of designers. We tried to emphasize colour, line and pattern."{{sfnb|McKay|2011|p=185}} These techniques can be seen within Thomson's work, whether it be Impressionism in ''The Pointers'' (1916–17); Art Nouveau in ''[[Northern River (painting)|Northern River]]'' (1914–15), ''[[:File:Tom Thomson Decorative Landscape, Birches.jpg|Decorative Landscape, Birches]]'' (1915–16), ''[[Spring Ice]]'' (1915–16) and ''The West Wind'' (1916–17); or [[Expressionism]] in ''After the Storm'' (1917) and ''Cranberry Marsh'' (1916).{{sfnb|Silcox|2015|p=68, 71}}

[[File:JEH MacDonald Fine Weather, Georgian Bay.jpg|thumb|left|[[J. E. H. MacDonald]], ''[[Fine Weather, Georgian Bay]]'', 1913. [[Art Gallery of Ontario]], [[Toronto]]. This painting depicts Thomson (right) alongside his friend [[A. Y. Jackson]] (left) tying up their canoe while silhouetted against the clear, still waters.{{sfnb|Silcox|2006|p=214}}]]

===Popular culture and other honours===

{{Quote box
 |quote  = <poem>Cedar and jagged fir
uplift sharp barbs
against the gray
and cloud-piled sky;
and in the bay
blown spume and windrift
and thin, bitter spray
snap
at the whirling sky;
and the pine trees
lean one way.
{{hidden begin}}
A wild duck calls
to her mate,
and the ragged
and passionate tones
stagger and fall,
and recover,
and stagger and fall,
on these stones—
are lost
in the lapping of water
on smooth, flat stones.
This is a beauty
of dissonance,
this resonance
of stony strand,
this smoky cry
curled over a black pine
like a broken
and wind-battered branch
when the wind
bends the tops of the pines
and curdles the sky
from the north.

This is the beauty
of strength
broken by strength
and still strong.
</poem>
